column1: When will COVID-19 cases caused by the Delta variant (B.1.617.2) exceed 350,000 in the UK?
column5: ['On or before 14 July 2021', 'Between 15 July and 28 July 2021', 'Between 29 July and 11 August 2021', 'Not before 12 August 2021']
column6: ['Technology', 'Health']
The latest report confirms an additional 57k cases pushing the total to 382k.

I'm expecting it to be case closed this morning at roughly 356-362K, but nothing certain yet Should hear within an hour or two based on previous reports FINAL: Results now in, higher than expected at 382,022 (maybe the mega-lab has finally started...)
It is past July 28, so decreasing the relevant probabilities to 0.
As of July 30, there is 324k cases, with a 37k weekly increase. Unless something drastic happens, it will occur in the next two weeks.

As we are at 324k cases as of the last update, all that needs to happen for the 350 000 number to be reached by the 11th of August is for the amount of confirmed or probable cases caused by the Delta variant to average ~2k/day or more for the next 2 weeks. It averaged over 5k a day for the last week.

The delta case numbers for 7/28 have come out and they total 324,000, a 37,000 increase over the 7/21 delta case numbers. I thought that there would be less than 34,000 new delta cases since that was the increase from 7/14-7/21 and the total covid case numbers from 7/21-7/28 were lower than from 7/14-7/21. So the delta case numbers continue to rise even though the total case numbers have come down.

RESULTS UPDATE: Perfect, new results are in at 37.4K for new sequenced delta cases to 28th July, and a new total of 324.2K confirmed and probable genotyped delta cases. Just under 38K cases were sequenced in total for this week: from past weeks it seems this is around the ‘normal’ throughput capacity we can expect before the mega-lab gets up to speed. Now extremely likely that next week’s result will be 350K+, and certainly by the week after that.
Repeating my rational for today's update, but given that rational, these numbers seem more sensible than the ones below.

Latest data suggests it will happen next week. https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-variants-genomically-confirmed-case-numbers/variants-distribution-of-case-data-30-july-2021 26k confirmed delta cases to go, new confirmed delta cases 37.5k. We are seeing only 25% week on week reductions in case numbers, which is not enough to prevent going past 350k this week. Further, despite the reduction in cases, we seem to have seen a rise in confirmed delta cases, so we may now be carrying out more variant tests than before.
324,192 this week with 37,427 sequenced over last 7 days. Pattern so far means we hit 350k next week.
Expecting 29-41K sequenced results this week, but given the surprises so far I won’t be shocked unless it’s under 25K or over 55K...

The latest data that has been released is for 21 July with ~286,000 delta variant cases, an increase in ~34,000 over 14 July. That leaves 64,000 cases until we meet the goal of 350,000 It seems that the pace of covid infections is slowing so I would be surprised if there is another >=34,000 increase in the 28 July data. Even if there is a 34,000 increase on 28 July that leaves 30,000 cases which unless there is a massive deceleration in cases makes it very likely that the ~350,000 case mark will occur in between 29 July and 11 August.
Updating forecast.
286,765 is the total number of confirmed (sequencing) and probable (genotyping) cases till July 21; last week the number of cases increased by ~34K. In any case, it won't exceed 350K next week.
Delta 286,765 as per data up to 21 July. , Up 33,716 from prior week.

The new data for the week ending Jul 21 is in. The total is at 286.7K, with 33.7K cases added in the previous week, continuing the trend of slow down that started in the previous week (36.8K the week ending Jul 14, 54.2K the week ending Jul 7). To get to above 350K by Jul 28, the next week will need to be above 63.3K cases, almost double the rate of the previous 2 weeks. That's unlikely, especially given the daily numbers we see here: https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/details/cases. So changing my previous forecast. In retrospect, the mistake I've made in the previous forecast was that I have ignored the last week as a "fluke", while it was the best data point I had.
Still leaving a possibility that something will happen this week but I doubt it more than my probability would suggest

Slow to update this week, been a busy week... 286,765 as of July 21 (+33,761), so testing rate is back to earlier levels. Almost no chance it'll be above 350k at next reporting unless the mega lab goes nuts this week. 90% chance it'll be above 350k on the Aug 4th reporting, 100% it'll be there by the 11th.

Let see: - total delta variant cases according to the source to the 23rd of July: 286,765 (https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-variants-genomically-confirmed-case-numbers/variants-distribution-of-case-data-23-july-2021). - so another 63,235 cases gets us to 350K all together. - in reality: almost all cases in the UK this wave are believed to be delta variant, so we're way past 350K already. - it looks like the source might only be reporting around 26% of true cases (comparing to a range of data from https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/details/cases). - we're getting about 47K new cases per day (https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/details/cases again), 26% x 47K = 12.22K, and at that rate we'll hit 350K around the the 29th of July. - in practice I believe that 26% figure is falling; it's more like 11% for the most recent week of data, 11% x 47K = 5.17K / day, hitting 350K around the 5th of August. - it's unclear if cases are still rising exponential (doubling every 14 days) or whether they're levelling off, but I don't expect them to fall sharply (because no measures have been put into place that would cause a sharp change).

Another week with only 33K cases. Would need to double that this week to hit 350K prior to July 28. On the other hand, only need 21K per week to get to 350 by August 11.

It perhaps also says something about the mixed messaging around Covid-19 data within the UK as well - in itself, the number of 'sequenced' delta cases is less useful, the valuable element being the proportion 33,716 of 34,132 that week, or 98.78% of all cases?

Again, this isn't about forecasting infection numbers so much as the vagaries of political and logistical chaos. Even with decline in sequencing, it's reasonable to suppose that 350k cases will be reached within the next 3 weeks, however the withdrawal of self-administerdclateral flow testing as the precursor to PCR diagnosis + govt indifference to mass infection mean it would be unwise to discount a further significant drop in official weekly case numbers.

The new mega-lab mentioned on previous comment is only operating at ~1/12th capacity due to delays, shortages and other issues: https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2021/07/18/exclusive-covid-testing-mega-lab-operating-less-10-per-cent/ And we still don't know how much this affects the ultra-high-throughput ePCR testing kit, which is capable of processing 150,000/day. The lab will also carry out genotype assay testing, which is more crucial to the outcome of this question, but there is no clear guidance when this will start. From the most recent SAGE report (12th July) Point 10: 'High prevalence also presents a challenge to testing, contact tracing and sequencing. If PCR testing and genomic sequencing capacity are overwhelmed, it may not be possible to rapidly identify a new variant'. So capacity is very much an issue, and near or at the current limit: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sage-93-minutes-coronavirus-covid-19-response-7-july-2021/sage-93-minutes-coronavirus-covid-19-response-7-july-2021 PHE (Public Health England) already provides sequencing expertise and support to other countries (through NVAP) but perhaps more significantly has sequenced samples from at least four other countries, and is expecting demand to increase: https://www.gov.uk/government/news/phe-to-provide-genomic-sequencing-support-to-partners-across-the-world Again this demand will limit available capacity each week and may cap increases (barring any mega-lab factor). So summing up: It's still a tussle between immediate demands and available capacity, and while a partially operational mega-lab would have the throughput to quickly increase capacity I suspect they are still weeks from operating efficiently. I'm hedging towards 40K results this week and 40-50K next week.

There are 253K cases up to Jul 14, with 36.8K new cases added in the previous week and 54.2K cases in the week before. Assuming that the 36.8K cases is a temporary "fluke" and the rate will actually grow to at least 48.5K / week in the next 2 weeks until July 28, this will get us to above 350K cases by July 28. Assuming a 20% chance that the rate will slow down to below 48.5K per week.
Opening forecast

Responding to the comment from jflom, I used https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-variants-genomically-confirmed-case-numbers/variants-distribution-of-case-data-16-july-2021 as the source instead, where a total of 253,049 cases of Delta were sequenced in the UK, with 36,800 new Delta cases this week. It gives a rough estimate of 14% increase every week. With this crude rate, Delta cases would exceed 350,000 by 4 August. However, there are many people infected with COVID or fully vaccinated in UK already, and reinfection is rare according to https://www.healthline.com/health-news/can-you-get-delta-variant-if-you-already-had-covid-19#Reinfection-remains-rare. Therefore, the rate would well be smaller than the crude estimate, and it would be harder to spread when more people are infected, since the uninfected ones would be the once-infected or vaccinated individuals. Using a decreasing rate of 12%, 10%, 8%, 6%, the cases would surpass 350,000 by 11 August.
I used a linear model since it seems like thats how the numbers have been evolving in the last 6 updates

This means 33,630 new Delta cases this week. It gives a rough estimate of 80% increase every week. With this crude rate, Delta cases would exceed 350,000 in the week of 2 August. However, there are many people infected with COVID or fully vaccinated in UK already, and reinfection is rare according to https://www.healthline.com/health-news/can-you-get-delta-variant-if-you-already-had-covid-19#Reinfection-remains-rare. Therefore, the rate would well be smaller than the crude estimate, and it would be harder to spread when more people are infected, since the uninfected ones would be the once-infected or vaccinated individuals. Using a decreasing rate of 1.8, 1.6, 1.4, 1.2, the cases would surpass 350,000 by the week of 9 August. Therefore, I would say the last two cases are equally likely.

A bump down in the number of samples genotyped or sequenced in the past week. That suggests to me that they were really maxing out their existing capacity the week before and couldn't do it again this past week, for whatever reason. If they get to ~50k/week for the next 2 weeks, we'll see 350k by July 28. If they don't, then we won't. So, were last week's lower numbers a minor glitch, or were the week before's higher numbers the result of a heroic effort coupled with perfect timing, planning, and luck that is unlikely to be repeated? We can't know the answer. But in the lab, whatever can go wrong generally does, so I'm going to weight the later bin a bit higher at this point.

The delta variant is the fastest-growing COVID variant in the UK at the moment, and in the 7-day periods ending 30 June and 23 June recorded a nearly 50% week-to-week increase in confirmed cases. If case numbers continue to grow at the same rate, the UK will be just shy of 350,000 delta variant cases by 14 July. Recent data suggests that the UK is entering another COVID peak, so it is likely that cases will be able to sustain this exponential growth for the near future. The delta variant has taken hold in the UK over the past few weeks despite robust vaccination efforts, so even as inoculation rates rise, the virus is unlikely to be slowed dramatically. Moreover, the UK just lifted almost all restrictions, and a return to lockdown seems unlikely given the present present political climate.

Despite continued growth in number of cases, (161k with a 50k rise from prior week as of June 30th), UK is still set to lift the final pandemic restrictions (https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-delta-variant-surges-in-u-k-boris-johnson-lifts-most-covid-19-curbs-11625506392). At the current rate, it seems that it will take about 3-4 weeks since June 30th to hit 350k cases; with more reopening, the less effectiveness of the vaccines as announced today, and the exponential nature of infectious diseases, I am revising my forecast to very low after July 28th.

Looking first at base rates in the UK, of the original strain: From 48K to 350K took 5 months From 350K to 700K took 1 month From 284K to 634K took 2.3 months Alpha variant statistics: The UK currently has 265K cases of the Alpha variant, which was first detected in fall 2020. It was 50% more transmissible than the original, and accounted for 90% of the UK cases at one point. Delta variant statistics: It is 50% more contagious than Alpha, and has rapidly overcome Alpha and now accounts for 90% of the UK cases. Compared to the original, Delta spreads approximately 2.25 faster, and 1.5 faster than Alpha. My estimate for the amount of time is therefore approximately 2.2 months as of June 9, which makes it around August 18. Note that Alpha never exceeded 350K, primarily because it was overtaken by another variant. So, there is also a chance that a new variant arrives that makes the Delta variant never exceed 350K. The variants of concern (Alpha Beta Gamma and Delta), all emerged late 2020. There is a rising variant of interest (Lambda) that may have increased transmissibility, but as potential resistance to the vaccine. For me, this means the probability for a new variant is quite low, and more probable that Lambda will overtake Delta, which is still a low probability (~2%) before August 11.

We can model the number of daily new Delta cases as exponential to approximate roughly how a virus spreads, by c*r^t where c is an initial constant, r is growth rate, and t is time. This exponential model is a common model for infections. Using https://www.bbc.com/news/health-57489740 we know up to June 16 there were almost 76,000 COVID cases caused by the Delta variant in the UK, and that the number of new COVID cases caused by the Delta variant is between around 90% and 100% of new COVID cases from around June 13 assuming trends continue (see graph in link). This is a reasonable assumption as the Delta variant continues to threaten the UK and be a major threat, and is corroborated as per this article which says the Delta variant accounts for 99% of COVID tests in the UK: https://www.usnews.com/news/health-news/articles/2021-06-18/delta-variant-makes-up-nearly-all-new-uk-coronavirus-cases. The number of new COVID cases on June 16 was 8808 and the number of new COVID cases on July 5 is 27100. Assuming Delta variant accounts for the lower bound of 90% of COVID cases for both values we can solve to get c=7927.2, r=1.0609. Assuming Delta variant accounts for the upper bound of 100% of COVID cases for both values we can solve to get c=8808, r=1.0609 (note r is the same; this makes sense based on how one solves the equation). We want to find T so that the integral from 0 to T of cr^t dt is at least 350,000-76,000 = 274,000. We can evaluate this integral to be c/ln r (r^T-1). If we take c=7927.2 we get T >= 18.83 and if we take C=8808 we get T >= 17.65. These dates correspond to July 6th and July 4th respectively, that is today. This may see like a harsh prediction but it makes sense considering the 7 day average of COVID cases in the UK since July 5th is around 25k and the 7 day average of COVID cases from the week before is around 16k. Assuming approximately 90% of COVID cases in the UK have been caused by Delta since this comes out to 41k*7*.9 which is around 258k COVID cases since June 21 caused by Delta, matching the earlier predictions. So I will in fact given the probability of this occurring before or on July 14 which is in over 1 week an 85% chance and the following event a 15% chance, giving a 0% chance for the last two events.

Seems that the sequencing/genotyping capabilities are far greater than once anticipated and with over 100k cases/wk if that threshold is possible we could possibly see before July 14.

Sequencing rate has increased from a high of 39.1K (week up to 9th June), to 51.7K (week to 30th June). Approx 130%. There is also evidence to support an increasing demand for genomic sequenced data, and there are clearly plenty of cases to test when including new surge testing across UK hotspots. So it seems likeliest that the final rate will be determined by throughput capacity. COG-UK have received plaudits for being at the forefront in both quantity and quality of results, but the process does involve a labour-intensive component across multiple labs, specialist kit and trained staff, so they are likely to be working near capacity. Testing numbers seem very unlikely to go down intentionally in the short term, using the same logic as above, and given that multiple labs are handling the process there seems minimal risk of large scale spoilt tests (although I'd need more evidence on this). A gain of 5-40% week on week seems very likely.

New Numbers! +50,824 to June 30 (161,981 total). ~52k sequenced in the last week means they're up to ~7.5k/day now and that may still increase. At current rate that puts us 25 days out (July 26) which is much sooner than I had expected. 7 day avg total cases is ~21k and increasing so they're only sequencing ~1/3 and there's still plenty of room to accelerate. Now it will undoubtedly cross 350k before the end of July. To be before July 14 they have to test over ~13.5k/day, which would be a very rapid increase over the next couple weeks so unlikely (but also not impossible). Next weeks numbers will be critical for the final tally.
As expected sequencing has increased, and by a slightly greater volume than expected

Currently, as per the site linked, there are approximately 162,000 confirmed cases for the delta variant. Additionally, we see that the last week added about 50,000 cases, which means that at the current rate, it would take about 4 weeks to hit 350,000.

If genetic characterization capacity remains constant, then we would expect 50.8 cases to be added each week. This would mean that 350k would barely be reached in the July 28 data. Testing capacity could be increased further. But what if it's not, and what if there's a glitch one week, and fewer than 50k are reported? Adding more weight to bin 3 for that possibility.

They increased genetic characterization capacity! I didn't think they would increase characterization substantially in this time frame, and I was wrong. We can now count on >=51k cases/week being added. Total now 162k. I don't think it's likely that they'll increase testing capacity further to 100k/week over the next 2 weeks, but I will no longer rule that out.

Delta variant cases reported since 5/20 are as follows: May 20 - 0, May 27 - 0, June 2 - 12431, June 9 - 42323, June 18 - 75953, June 23 - 111157, July 2 - 161981. Plotting this out does somewhat seem like the start of some exponential function. If we run OLS just as a sanity check, we get 8/15/2021 as the date in which more than 350k cases are exceeded. It's worth noting this is the slowest of slowest cases (reported linearly throughout) and is quite close to the August 12 cutoff for the last option. Hence, if August 12 comes and the UK hasn't reported more than 350,000 cases, the UK would've likely had serious slowdowns in the their testing protocols. Considering tests are conducted twice a week in England at no charge, it seems like the country has a robust testing schedule ahead.
Amending for a likely false assumption that cases confirmed right now are representative of active cases.

In the last week, there were 51,000 new Delta variant cases in the UK, bringing the total to about 162,000 cases, meaning we're asking the question, how long will it take for 188,000 cases to be reported. Due to testing limitations, and weekly trends, the earliest, I think the UK could reasonably hit this total by is July 25th (using the most recent weekly increase), but it is more likely to hit this total around August 3rd (averaging some of the weekly increases). That being said, current research is showing that a new, likely more transmissible strain (Delta plus) will be hitting the UK soon. Since a person cannot be affected by multiple viruses at once, the more transmissible strain can compete with the Delta strain and slow its growth. This question isn't about how fast Delta will spread; the limiting factor is going to be sequencing and genotyping capabilities. The UK has ~9k new cases per day, 99% of which are the Delta variant. In the week ending June 16, in the ballpark of 47k Delta cases were confirmed, yet only 33.6k (~71%) were added to the figure being forecasted. In the previous week, in the ballpark of 41k Delta cases were added, but only 29.9k (~73%) were added to the forecast figure. So, as long as ~72% of all Delta samples continue to be sequenced and genotyped, if cases continue to grow as they have so far, then we'll see 350k by the end of July. However, if more restrictions are put in place, then it won't.
